<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Theories of Developmental Psychology</title>
    <style>
        :root {
            --primary: #2c3e50;
            --accent: #3498db;
            --bg: #f9f9f9;
            --white: #ffffff;
            --text: #444;
        }

        body {
            font-family: 'Segoe UI', Roboto, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;
            line-height: 1.6;
            color: var(--text);
            background-color: var(--bg);
            margin: 0;
        }

        header {
            background: var(--primary);
            color: var(--white);
            padding: 3rem 1rem;
            text-align: center;
        }

        .container {
            max-width: 1000px;
            margin: -2rem auto 2rem;
            padding: 0 1rem;
        }

        .theory-card {
            background: var(--white);
            border-radius: 8px;
            padding: 2rem;
            margin-bottom: 2rem;
            box-shadow: 0 4px 15px rgba(0,0,0,0.05);
            border-top: 5px solid var(--accent);
        }

        h2 { color: var(--primary); margin-top: 0; }
        
        .theory-meta {
            display: flex;
            gap: 20px;
            font-size: 0.9rem;
            color: #7f8c8d;
            margin-bottom: 1rem;
            font-style: italic;
        }

        .concept-grid {
            display: grid;
            grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(250px, 1fr));
            gap: 20px;
            margin-top: 1.5rem;
        }

        .concept-item {
            background: #f0f7ff;
            padding: 1.2rem;
            border-radius: 6px;
            border-left: 3px solid var(--accent);
        }

        .quiz-box {
            background: #2c3e50;
            color: white;
            padding: 2rem;
            border-radius: 8px;
            text-align: center;
        }

        .btn {
            background: var(--accent);
            color: white;
            border: none;
            padding: 12px 25px;
            border-radius: 25px;
            cursor: pointer;
            font-size: 1rem;
            transition: transform 0.2s;
        }

        .btn:hover { transform: translateY(-2px); }

        footer { text-align: center; padding: 3rem; color: #95a5a6; }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

<header>
    <h1>Major Theories of Development</h1>
    <p>Exploring the frameworks that define human growth across the lifespan.</p>
</header>

<div class="container">

    <article class="theory-card">
        <div class="theory-meta">
            <span>Focus: Cognitive Development</span>
            <span>Key Figure: Jean Piaget</span>
        </div>
        <h2>1. Cognitive Stage Theory</h2>
        <p>Piaget proposed that children are "little scientists" who actively construct their understanding of the world through four distinct stages.</p>
        
        <div class="concept-grid">
            <div class="concept-item">
                <strong>Sensorimotor (0-2y)</strong><br>
                Learning through senses and motor actions. Key milestone: <em>Object Permanence</em>.
            </div>
            <div class="concept-item">
                <strong>Preoperational (2-7y)</strong><br>
                Symbolic thought and language emerge. Characterized by <em>Egocentrism</em>.
            </div>
            <div class="concept-item">
                <strong>Concrete Operational (7-11y)</strong><br>
                Logical thought about physical events. Mastery of <em>Conservation</em>.
            </div>
            <div class="concept-item">
                <strong>Formal Operational (12y+)</strong><br>
                Abstract reasoning and hypothetical thinking develop.
            </div>
        </div>
    </article>

    <article class="theory-card" style="border-top-color: #e67e22;">
        <div class="theory-meta">
            <span>Focus: Psychosocial Development</span>
            <span>Key Figure: Erik Erikson</span>
        </div>
        <h2 style="color: #d35400;">2. Psychosocial Theory</h2>
        <p>Unlike Piaget, Erikson focused on the entire lifespan, suggesting that social impulses and cultural demands drive development through eight stages of "crises."</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Identity vs. Role Confusion (Adolescence):</strong> The search for self and personal values.</li>
            <li><strong>Generativity vs. Stagnation (Middle Adulthood):</strong> The need to create or nurture things that will outlast the individual.</li>
            <li><strong>Integrity vs. Despair (Late Adulthood):</strong> Reflecting on life with either satisfaction or regret.</li>
        </ul>
    </article>

    <article class="theory-card" style="border-top-color: #27ae60;">
        <div class="theory-meta">
            <span>Focus: Sociocultural Context</span>
            <span>Key Figure: Lev Vygotsky</span>
        </div>
        <h2 style="color: #27ae60;">3. Sociocultural Theory</h2>
        <p>Vygotsky argued that social interaction and culture are fundamental to cognitive development. Learning happens first on a social level, then on an individual level.</p>
        
        <div class="concept-item" style="background: #eef9f1; border-left-color: #27ae60;">
            <strong>The Zone of Proximal Development (ZPD):</strong> 
            The gap between what a learner can do without help and what they can do with guidance. This is where the most effective "Scaffolding" occurs.
        </div>
    </article>

    <section class="quiz-box">
        <h3>Test Your Knowledge</h3>
        <p>Which theorist emphasized that learning is a social process facilitated by a "More Knowledgeable Other"?</p>
        <div style="margin-top: 1rem;">
            <button class="btn" onclick="alert('Try again! Piaget focused more on individual exploration.')">Piaget</button>
            <button class="btn" onclick="alert('Correct! Vygotsky focused on social interaction.')">Vygotsky</button>
            <button class="btn" onclick="alert('Not quite! Erikson focused on psychosocial conflicts.')">Erikson</button>
        </div>
    </section>

</div>

<footer>
    <p>&copy; 2026 Developmental Psych Course Portal</p>
</footer>

</body>
</html>
